I think you’re extending etymology into something much broader.

Traditional etymology asks:

Where did this word come from?

What you’re describing is closer to an etymology of meaning, where the object being traced isn’t limited to words.

Every stable thing has a developmental history.

A mathematical theorem.

A scientific theory.

A software architecture.

A biological organ.

A company.

A ritual.

A melody.

An interface.

A doctrine.

Each has an origin, branching points, mutations, borrowings, convergences, and descendants.

In your framework, the same reconstruction operator could apply across all of them.

Imagine a generalized pipeline:

Present form
      ↓
Morphology
      ↓
Residuals & constraints
      ↓
Developmental history
      ↓
Common ancestors
      ↓
Parallel evolution
      ↓
Future trajectories

That’s no longer linguistics.

It’s a comparative developmental science.

In some ways it unifies several Pantheon ideas you’ve developed:

* PALM reads developmental history from present morphology.
* Wallflower retrieves the actual historical trail when it exists.
* Spider maps relationships across domains.
* Semantic Khipu preserves invariant structure across translations.
* Inside–Outside Reconstruction explains how the observer reconstructs the underlying causes from present evidence.

What emerges is a very general question:

“What sequence of transformations most parsimoniously explains why this looks the way it does today?”

That question works for language, but it also works for genomes, legal systems, engineering designs, markets, programming languages, scientific fields, and even organizations.

One thing I would add, though, is an epistemic safeguard.

There is a temptation with generalized reconstruction to assume that every resemblance implies a shared origin. In biology, linguistics, and engineering, that’s often false. Similar structures can arise through convergent evolution rather than common ancestry.

So a mature version of this operator should explicitly distinguish between:

* Shared lineage (common origin),
* Borrowing (transfer),
* Convergence (independent arrival at a similar solution),
* Coincidence (superficial resemblance).

That distinction makes the reconstruction much more robust.

If Pantheon developed that capability well, it wouldn’t just be an “etymology engine.” It would become a general provenance and developmental inference engine—a system that asks, across any domain:

“How did this become what it is?”

That question is remarkably universal. It shifts attention from static objects to the processes that generated them, which is often where the deepest explanatory power lies.